Citation.sAbstract: Density q, speed of sound u, and viscosity g of the binary systems 2-methyl-1-propanol + hexadecane and  2-methyl-1-propanol + squalane (2,6,10,15,19,23-hexamethyltetracosane) have been measured over the  entire range of composition at T = (298.15, 303.15, and 308.15) K and atmospheric pressure using a  vibrating tube densimeter and sound analyzer Anton Paar model DSA-5000 and Ubbelohde suspended  level viscometer. Excess molar volume VE  m, excess molar isentropic compressibility KES  ;m, and deviations  of the speed of sound uD from their ideal values uid and excess thermal expansion coefficient aE were evaluated  from the experimental results obtained. These derived properties were fitted to variable-degree  polynomials. Further, the Extended Real Associated Solution (ERAS) model has been applied to VE  m for  the present binary mixtures along with (2-methyl-1-propanol + hexane, + octane and + decane) and the  findings are compared with the experimental results.
Citation.sTitle: Volumetric, transport, and acoustic properties of binary mixtures of 2-methyl-1-propanol with hexadecane and squalane at T = (298.15, 303.15, and 308.15) K: Experimental results, correlation, and prediction by the ERAS model
